occurrences.line_text: For very fell despight, which she conceiued,
But kicks, and squals, and shriekes for fell despight:
But she thereat was wroth, that for despight
At last proud Radigund with fell despight,
Her heart gan grudge, for very deepe despight
That with most fell despight and deadly hate,
And sending to the Souldan in despight
All flaming with reuenge and furious despight.
To keepe out guyle, and malice, and despight,
Out of their breasts, with furious despight.
To his first rage, and yeeld to his despight;
He brayd aloud for very fell despight;
Made kill her selfe for very hearts despight,
That forst her turne againe in her despight,
And proud despight of his selfe pleasing mynd,
Who executes her wicked will, with worse despight.
And oft recuile to shunne his sharpe despight.
And both inflam'd with furious despight:
I may auenge him of so foule despight.
The meede of his desert for that despight,
As in despight to be so fowle abused
At whose calamity, for more despight
Because of one, that wrought him fowle despight.
And greedy to auenge that vile despight,
And him auenge of that so villenous despight.
For fell despight, to be so sorely crost;
Three mightie en'mies did him most despight,
Burning with inward rancour and despight,
Tell me what worlds despight, or heauens yre
Wrought to Sir Calidore so foule despight;
He woxe nigh mad with wrath and fell despight,
His rancorous despight did not releasse,
To this attempt, to wreake his hid despight,
That was to him on earth the deadliest despight.
To whom foule Infamie, and fell Despight
Yond Lady and her Squire with foule despight
He driuen was to ground in selfe despight;
All saue the shepheard, who for fell despight
That euen his hart for very fell despight,
That made him almost mad for fell despight.
With which he drew him forth, euen in his own despight.
With so fell force and villeinous despighte,
Which when she heard, as in despightfull wise,
Reproch despightfull, carelesse, and vnkind;
But inly thought of that despightfull deede
To heare him threaten so despightfully.
And at him throwes it most despightfully.
Would for it selfe redresse, and punish such despights.
Her dalliance he despisd, and follies did forsake.
As one that loathed life, and yet despisd to dye.
His sorrowes cause to be of her despis'd.
Despisd and troden downe of all that ouerran.
That had despisde so chast and faire a dame,
The angry beasts not rashly to despise,
And offred hope of comfort did despise:
But if that carelesse heauens (quoth she) despise
As to despise so courteous seeming part,
(So Loue the dread of daunger doth despise)
Such superfluities they would despise,
His daughter gan despise his drouping day,
As threatning to deuoure all, that his powre despise.
Else she will slip away, and all our drift despise.
For great rebuke it is, loue to despise,
Strokes, wounds, wards, weapons, all they did despise,
That whylome in your minde wont to despise them all.
The grace of his Creator doth despise,
Not to despise that dame, which lou'd him liefe,
And wreake him selfe on them, that him despise.
That doth despise the dainties of the towne.
Yet Calidore did not despise him quight,
But them despised all; for all was in her powre.
That he his lookes despised, and his boast dispraized.
True loue despiseth shame, when life is cald in dread.
But she them all despiseth for great pride.
Hope to escape his venemous despite,
And wicked doome, to Iewes despiteous
Against her rode, full of despiteous ire,
Nathlesse it fell with so despiteous dreare
Another knight in his despiteous pryde;
The mortall steele despiteously entayld
That none did others safety despize,
That noble heart as great dishonour doth despize.
Which scornefull offer, Blandamour gan soone despize.
With which he dares our offers thus despize.
Yet rather then she kindnesse would despize,
The saluage nation doth all dread despize:
Quite ouerthrow, who now ginnes to despize
That euen the Prince his basenesse did despize,
And that the more she did all loue despize,
His layes, his loues, his lookes she did them all despize.
Then when they had despoild her tire and call,
Into a goodly lodge, and gan despoile
Auoided quite, she gan her selfe despoile,
He wist not, how him to despoile of life,
Each other of loues bitter fruit despoile.
First she doth them of warlike armes despoile,
Whom when thou mayst, thou dost of arms despoile,
Acrates sonnes despoyld,
Least saluage beastes her person haue despoyld:
And lastly to despoyle of knightly bannerall.
And of his armes despoyled easily,
Of her dew honour was despoyled quight,
Their girlonds rent, their bowres despoyled all;
Both of their publicke praise had them despoyled,
Nor none but beasts may be of her despoyled:
Or by some other violence despoyled.
Despoyled of those ioyes and iollyhead,
But Tristram then despoyling that dead knight
Where he him fou[n]d despoyling all with maine & might.
For he despysd to tread in dew degree,
To take to his new loue, and leaue her old despysd.
Who her despysd (ah who would her despyse?)
Despysde, and all the fawning of the flatterer.
Who her despysd (ah who would her despyse?)
And eke that age despysed nicenesse vaine,
Ne euer once did looke vp from her desse,
Gainst which the second troupe dessignment makes;
But Penda, fearefull of like desteny,
Thou doest effect in destined descents,
But who can turne the streame of destinee,
You, whom my hard auenging destinie
Or shunne the death ordaynd by destinie?
Me giuen by eternall destinie,
Her deare sonnes destinie to her to tell,
Vpon thee heapt a direfull destinie,
But vnto them what destinie was assynd,
Like as his mother prayd the Destinie,
That seemed nought but death mote be her destinie.
Ay me (quoth she) what wicked destinie?
Whose parents deare, whilest equall destinies
Ah wretch (quoth he) thy destinies withstand
As chicken newly hatcht, from dreaded destiny.
The hellish Harpies, prophets of sad destiny.
But the streight course of heauenly destiny,
And do by all dew meanes thy destiny fulfill.
When the full time prefixt by destiny,
But ah, who can deceiue his destiny,
Ne can thy irreuocable destiny be weft?
Vnwares defrauded his intended destiny.
But read thou shepheard, read what destiny,
All destitute of helpe doth headlong fall,
For who can shun the chaunce, that dest'ny doth ordaine?
Bewraying him, that did of late destroy
And greeu'd, to thinke how foe did him destroy,
In case he could that monstrous beast destroy,
Of Amazons, whom Pyrrhus did destroy,
Who, after Greekes did Priams realme destroy,
Should fetch againe, and finally destroy
For neither they by force could him destroy,
That Monster can be maistred or destroyd:
Of her rich spoyles, whom he had earst destroyd,
Good Knights and Ladies true, and many else destroyd.
Creeping behinde him still to haue destroyde:
It she reduced, but himselfe destroyed quight.
She had destroyed two and twenty more.
If yet he were aliue, or to destruction brought.
Throughout the world, and to destruction brought.
But glauncing by, deceiu'd him of that he desynd.
The arrow, to his deadly marke desynde,
The wicked driftes of trayterous desynes,
That she desyrd th'abridgement of her fate,
Whereat soft knocking, entrance he desyrd.
Or if ought higher were then that, did it desyre.
Yet all that might not slake her sensuall desyre.
To turne your course, I would to heare desyre,
And him beside marcht amorous Desyre,
And euermore he gently did desyre,
Vnto her ran with greedie great desyre,
When good was onely for it selfe desyred,
She claim'd that to her selfe, as Ladies det,
But to forbeare doth not forgiue the det.
The crowne, which Vortiger did long detaine:
The certaine cause of Artegals detaine;
Yet she him still detaines in captiue hold
Detaynd, yet Fortune not with all this wrong
For she by force is still fro me detayned,
He spued vp his gorge, that all did him deteast.
Had borne him, or his tract she mote detect:
Like neuer yet did liuing eye detect;
Yet dropping fresh in hand did her detect,
For feare she should of lightnesse be detected:
And all that life preserued, did detest:
And all his fained kindnesse did detest.
That detestable sight him much amazde,
A daungerous and detestable place,
And she that vertue loues and vice detests
Her name was hight Detraction, and her dwelling
And with vniust detraction him did beard;
For such your kind regard, I can but rest your detter.
Were throwne by Pyrrha and Deucalione:
Also to win Deucalions daughter bright,
The same by my deuice I vndertake
So fashioned a Porch with rare deuice,
A worke of rare deuice, and wondrous wit.
Nor hart could wish for any queint deuice,
Or could be fram'd by workmans rare deuice;
The goodly seruice, the deuicefull sights,
Some Clarkes doe doubt in their deuicefull art,
Deuices, dreames, opinions vnsound,
That none but death for euer can deuide;
Whom they in equall pray hope to deuide,
A great aduenture, which did him from them deuide.
Encloseth Corke with his deuided flood;
Deuided be betwixt you here in sight,
And all the sea, deuided each from either:
There was the speedy Tamar, which deuides
Far from all neighbours, that her deuilish deedes
And by her deuilish arts thought to preuaile,
Yet to auenge his deuilish despight,
She askt, what deuill had her thither brought,
The one a feend, the other an incarnate deuill.
Whom neither dread of God, that deuils bindes,
And eke himselfe had craftily deuisd
Eftsoones deuisd redresse for such annoyes;
He then deuisde himselfe how to disguise;
Her Lordes and Ladies all this while deuise
Can now deuise to quit a thrall from such a plight?
Who glad to gain such fauour, gan deuise,
With all the court'sies, that she could deuise.
Thus as they gan of sundry things deuise,
Then meanes I gan deuise for his deliuerance.
Yet others she more vrgent did deuise:
She could deuise, and thousand waies inuent,
And set them forth, as well he could deuise.
But if ought else that I mote not deuise,
Now this, now that twixt them they did deuise,
Conceiu'd a bold deuise, and thus bespake;
She gan for me deuise a grieuous punishment.
In stead of yellow lockes she did deuise,
But why do we deuise of others ill,
He gan deuise, how her he reskew mought,
So diuersely each one did sundrie doubts deuise.
And all things did deuise, and all things dooe,
But on their common harmes together did deuise.
Both through a forest ryding did deuise
But read to me, by what deuise or wit,
To come, where he his dolors did deuise,
In milder tearmes, as list them to deuise:
Now gan he in his grieued minde deuise,
Ne wist he what to thinke, or to deuise,
There dead on ground. What doe ye then deuise
They did this complot twixt them selues deuise,
Were best deuise for this your louers smart,
Yet could she not deuise by any wit,
The hardy boy, as they deuised had,
Thereof deuising shortly to be wroke,
Deuising what to doe, he nigh espyde
And that deare Crosse vpon your shield deuizd,
Couer'd with lids deuiz'd of substance sly,
And Pleasures porter was deuizd to bee,
The great Magitian Merlin had deuiz'd,
She there deuiz'd a wondrous worke to frame,
Therewith, as thing deuiz'd her to defame.
And to accord them all, this meanes deuiz'd:
And eft againe deuiz'd some what to say,
And there a piteous ditty new deuiz'd,
As each one had his furnitures deuiz'd.
Now she deuiz'd amongst the warlike rout
His father Dolon had deuiz'd of late
So as they had deuiz'd, sir Artegall
Which warlike vses had deuiz'd of yore.
Deuiz'd all goodly meanes, from her to driue
But friendly each did others prayse deuize
What needs of daintie dishes to deuize,
Let vs deuize of ease and euerlasting rest.
Of ease or rest I may not yet deuize;
And other whiles vaine toyes she would deuize
And did of ioy and iollitie deuize,
That of this lands first conquest did deuize,
Might be maintaynd, and each gan diuersely deuize.
Long worke it were, and needlesse to deuize
So faire a place, as Nature can deuize:
Whom, to be Paridell he did deuize;
Such as the maker selfe could best by art deuize.
But rather gan in troubled mind deuize,
Deuize how to enlarge him out of hould.
Then gan the other further to deuize
And gan eftsoones deuize to be aueng'd for it.
The Prince staid not his aunswere to deuize,
With all the tortures, that he could deuize,
Which haue so goodly, as ye can deuize,
Of her good fame, and further gan deuize,
He can deuize this counter-cast of slight,
He gan deuize, to be aueng'd anew
To ioyne with him and vengeance to deuize,
Then gan they to deuize what course to take:
But of her dainty flesh they did deuize
And some of them gan mongst themselues deuize,
They are, which fortunes doe by vowes deuize,
Then all that he could doe, or euer deuize:
Ne can deuized be of mortall wit;
It fortuned, as they deuized had,
Deuized hath, and to her louer told.
Deuized by the Gods, for to asswage
And when he had deuized of her case,
Deuized to worke delight, was gathered there,
Deuizing, how that doughtie turnament
Deuizing of his loue more, then of daunger drad.
Deuoid of outward sense, and natiue strength,
His heauie head, deuoide of carefull carke,
In perfect loue, deuoide of hatefull strife,
Which to auenge, Sir Deuon him did dight,
The Cornish and the Deuonish confines;
And Debons shayre was, that is Deuonshyre:
For of deuotion he had little care,
That day and night said his deuotion,
With great deuotion, and with litle zeale:
And turning his feare to faint deuotion,
That should their mindes vp to deuotion call,
They mote the better tend to their deuotion.
From his deuotion streight he troubled was;
Marres blind Deuotions mart, and fals
To haue attonce deuour'd her tender corse:
To haue deuourd, so soone as day he spyde,
Or quite deuourd her beauties scornefull grace.
Are quite deuourd, and brought to nought by little bits?
Deuoure their dam; on whom while so he gazd,
O how great wonder would your thoughts deuoure,
As threatning to deuoure all, that his powre despise.
Ran towards, to deuoure those vnexpected guests.
Who not content so fowly to deuoure
As if that each ment other to deuoure;
And afterwards themselues doth cruelly deuoure.
And fire deuoure the ayre, and hell them quight,
And gaping greedy wide, did streight deuoure
Where still the stronger doth the weake deuoure,
For twelue of them he did by times deuoure,
Vnto a dreadfull Monster to deuoure,
As if that he attonce would me deuoure.
With that ran at him, as he would deuoure
To be aueng'd on him, and to deuoure his corse.
And straungers to deuoure, which on their border
Was readie oft his owne hart to deuoure,
Of late deuoured bodies did appeare,
Had in his greedie gulfe deuoured deepe,
It now deuoures with flames and scorching heat,
Those he deuoures, they say, both flesh and bone:
With murdrous rauine, and deuouring might
His byting sword, and his deuouring speare,
Does tremble: for his deepe deuouring iawes
And from his wide deuouring ouen sent
Of Mulcibers deuouring element;
For whiles they fly that Gulfes deuouring iawes,
And their deuouring couetize restraynd,
And this deuouring Sea, that naught doth spare,
For dread of their deuouring enemie,
Deuouring, euen that halfe-gnawen snake,
Vpon her beades deuoutly penitent;
And for his safetie gan deuoutly pray;
Into the graue, and gan deuoutly sweare;
For fear the cruell Feends should thee vnwares deuowre.
I wast my life, and doe my daies deuowre
That the cold steele through piercing, did deuowre
When I awoke, and found her place deuoyd,
He flong it from him, and deuoyd of dreed,
Had she not bene deuoyd of mortall slime,
Oft purposes, oft riddles he deuysd,
And that new creature borne without her dew,
Die is my dew: yet rew my wretched state
Both those the lawrell girlonds to the victor dew.
Is not enough, that thrust from heauen dew
That she conceiu'd; and trebling the dew time,
And empty sides deceiued of their dew,
With dew repast they had recured well,
Were hardned with that holy water dew,
By dew desert of noble cheualree,
To flie the vengeance for his outrage dew;
His cruell sport, in stead of sorrow dew;
To let a wearie wretch from her dew rest,
If I or thou dew vengeance doe forbeare,
And not regard dew right and iust desarts?
When they would striue dew reason to exceed;
If where those knights for feare of dew vengeaunce
Through goodly mixture of complexions dew;
For he despysd to tread in dew degree,
Varlet, this place most dew to me I deeme,
Others sweet words, dropping like honny dew;
And euer as he went, dew watch vpon him kept.
Till partiall Paris dempt it Venus dew,
And to the Prince bowing with reuerence dew,
Suffise, that I haue done my dew in place.
There when they rested had a season dew,
But in good order, and with dew regard;
The knights there entring, did him reuerence dew
And all mens harts in dew obedience held:
The which was dew in his dead fathers dayes:
By dew successe, and all their Nephewes late,
Till aged Hely by dew heritage it gaynd.
And all their Ofspring, in their dew descents,
That themselues dipping in the siluer dew,
To enter in, and reape the dew reward:
To crowne his golden lockes with honour dew;
For death nor daunger from thy dew reliefe
Till that by dew degrees and long pretence,
And do by all dew meanes thy destiny fulfill.
The Britons, for their sinnes dew punishment,
That of the time doth dew aduauntage take;
And findeth dew effect or soone or late.
Yet not escaped from the dew reward
With reason dew the passion to subdew,
Sith I her dew reward cannot restore:
Her berth was of the wombe of Morning dew,
Till to her dew perfection she was ripened.
Some of them washing with the liquid dew
And her loose lockes to dight in order dew,
Long thus I woo'd her with dew obseruance,
To heape on him dew vengeaunce for his hire.
With vigilant regard, and dew attent,
I loath as doung, ne deeme my dew reward:
Did raine into her lap an hony dew,
Of her dew honour was despoyled quight,
To giue him the reward for such vile outrage dew.
And chalenging the Virgin as his dew.
Yet nathelesse to her, as her dew right,
With pearly dew sprinkling the morning grasse:
To be embaulm'd, and sweat out dainty dew,
And with few drops thereof did softly dew
Ye will recount to vs in order dew
Faire lawnds, to take the sunne in season dew;
Thou doest not know the causes, nor their courses dew.
Them selues thereto preparde in order dew;
To doe those workes, to them appointed dew:
And forced it, the honour that is dew
Forget his patience, and yeeld vengeaunce dew
To pay each with his owne is right and dew.
And sude and sought with all the seruice dew:
Ne rested he himselfe but natures dew,
The which did pype and sing her prayses dew,
With dayly seruice and attendance dew,
And in dew time a mayden child forth brought.
Their welheads spring, and are with moisture dewd;
Dew'd with her drops of bountie Soueraine,
All dewfull seruice voide of thoughts imp[u]re:
Wherein the Hermite dewly wont to say
They for vs fight, they watch and dewly ward,
Appointed to attend her dewly day and night.
Into their comely tresses dewly drest,
Endite I would as dewtie doth excite;
He liues, that shall him pay his dewties last,
He did her seruice dewtifull, and sewed
Those for Gods sake his dewty was to entertaine.
Did dewty to their Lady, as became;
His dewy lockes did drop with brine apace,
That following his chace in dewy morne,
And Howell Dha shall goodly well indew
The sacred Diademe in peeces rent,
Who on him tooke the royall Diademe,
Vnder his Diademe imperiall:
Wearing a Diademe embattild wide
Or that with Diademe hath euer crowned beene.
With crownes and Diademes, & titles vaine,
And on the top a Diall told the timely howres.
As rocke of Diamond stedfast euermore.
But all of Diamond perfect pure and cleene
Prince Arthur gaue a boxe of Diamond sure,
Strong Diamond, but not so stout a knight,
But horse and foote knew Diamond to wield:
With curtaxe vsed Diamond to smite,
Till Diamond disdeigning long delay
That seem'd a rocke of Diamond it could riue,
Yet like a Diamond of rich regard,
Sometimes Diana he her takes to bee,
As faire Diana in fresh sommers day
And to Diana calling lowd for ayde,
Such as Diana by the sandie shore
Thereat Diana gan to smile, in scorne
That for his sake Diana did lament,
Not that same famous Temple of Diane,
By Dianes meanes, who was Hippolyts frend,
Was out of Dianes fauour, as it then befell.
To search the secret haunts of Dianes company.
But or some Goddesse, or of Dianes crew,
All which compacted made a goodly Diapase.
Iust Dice, wise Eunomie, myld Eirene,
Then Artegall himselfe dicouering plaine,
Lo I the man, whose Muse whilome did maske,
Wherein old dints of deepe wounds did remaine,
Yet armes till that time did he neuer wield:
His angry steede did chide his foming bitt,
Full iolly knight he seemd, and faire did sitt,
But of his cheere did seeme too solemne sad;
Yet nothing did he dread, but euer was ydrad.
Which of all earthly things he most did craue;
And euer as he rode, his hart did earne
Yet she much whiter, but the same did hide
And ouer all a blacke stole she did throw,
Behind her farre away a Dwarfe did lag,
Did poure into his Lemans lap so fast,
That euery wight to shrowd it did constrain,
Did spred so broad, that heauens light did hide,
Did spred so broad, that heauens light did hide,
When weening to returne, whence they did stray,
But th'other halfe did womans shape retaine,
His gall did grate for griefe and high disdaine,
That soone to loose her wicked bands did her constraine.
With loathly frogs and toades, which eyes did lacke,
Which swarming all about his legs did crall,
But still did follow one vnto the end,
And often knockt his brest, as one that did repent.
And after asked him, if he did know
